transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Hi, thank you so much for calling Viagra. My name is Jessie. Can I get your first and last name?

Speaker 2: First is Eric, E-R-I-C, and last is Navarette, N-A-V-A-R-R-E-T-E.

Speaker 1: Okay, perfect. Mr. Navarette, can I get your zip code?

Speaker 2: 89074.

Speaker 1: And you're at 339 Humboldt South Drive in Henderson, Nevada, correct?

Speaker 2: That's correct.

Speaker 1: Okay, super. All right, so you recently placed an order yesterday, the doctor approved it, and this should be shipping out shortly.

Speaker 1: Is there anything else I can help you with in the meantime?

Speaker 2: Yeah, I noticed that there's an automatic refill, and I don't want to have that automatic refill.

Speaker 1: Oh, yeah, no, no, no, absolutely. Let me just take a look there. This here should just be – let me set it up so it's – what is this?

Speaker 1: As needed, so you can order whenever you want.

Speaker 2: Okay.

Speaker 1: Bear with me a moment, but I also want to make sure you still have access to your refills and that your prescription remains active.

Speaker 2: All right, so what I've done here is this. I've basically frozen everything for six months.

Speaker 1: All that means is you can order whenever you like. You're not going to get some rando stuff in the mail, and that's it.

Speaker 2: To keep your prescription active, in the event you do not place an order in six months' time,

Speaker 1: you get one refill at the end of six months to keep your prescription active, and that's it. Okay?

Speaker 2: So if I even call – are you going to notify me? Because I might forget.

Speaker 1: Oh, yeah, no, no, absolutely. You should get a notification.

Speaker 2: Will you let me know ahead of time, hey, your refill's coming up, or are you going to notify me my refill's on the way?

Speaker 1: No, you should get something like – notification should be ahead of time. It should be about five days ahead.

Speaker 2: Before it's sent out?

Speaker 1: Yeah.

Speaker 2: Okay. All right.

Speaker 1: All right.

Speaker 2: There's no way to just remove the six – so what you're saying is that once you remove that six-month thing

Speaker 1: or whatever the case may be, that cancels the whole prescription. Is that what you're saying?

Speaker 2: That's correct.

Speaker 1: So if I didn't care for it, I don't like it, I can call before that and say, hey, you know what, just cancel the whole thing?

Speaker 2: Yeah, absolutely, absolutely.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: All right, anything else?

Speaker 1: All right, sounds good.

Speaker 2: Okay, thank you so much. Okay, bye-bye.

Speaker 1: Bye, everybody.

Speaker 2: Bye.
